{{nihongo foot|'''''Star Soldier'''''|スターソルジャー|Sutā Sorujā|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[shoot 'em up]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Hudson Soft]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] and the [[MSX]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/star-soldier|title=Star Soldier (1986)|website=MobyGames|access-date=2021-10-16|archive-date=2017-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914194654/http://www.mobygames.com/game/star-soldier|url-status=live}}</ref> The player pilots the starship "Caesar", travelling through [[space station]]s occupied by powerful supercomputers known as "Starbrains" who threaten the galactic empire. ''Star Soldier'' greatly resembles the earlier  arcade game ''[[Star Force]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hg101.kontek.net/starsoldier/starsoldier.htm|title=Hardcore Gaming 101: Star Soldier|website=hg101.kontek.net|access-date=2021-10-16|archive-date=2017-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827000914/http://hg101.kontek.net/starsoldier/starsoldier.htm|url-status=live}}</ref>

Mobile versions were released on January 26, 2001, in Japan as '''''Star Soldier Special+''''' in 2004, '''''Star Soldier SP Arcade''''' in 2005 and {{nihongo foot|'''''Star Soldier Fukkoku-Ban'''''|スターソルジャー 復刻版|Sutāsorujā fukkoku-ban|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} in 2008;<ref>[https://archive.today/20141123004937/http://appli.docomomarket.ne.jp/detail/BRW001_PM1_001;jsessionid=5F68EB5A7ABF0BA437118B2367DFF564-110910.003?form.appliId=10000002354 ''ｽﾀｰｿﾙｼﾞｬｰ復刻版''] an 2008's Mobile version in Docomomarket (in Japanese)</ref> they were also released for Palm OS in November 2001 in Japan and iOS on January 4, 2012, in United States.

''Star Soldier'' has spawned numerous sequels, starting with ''[[Super Star Soldier]]'' on the [[TurboGrafx-16|PC Engine]]. It was ported to the [[Game Boy Advance]] in 2004 in [[Japan]] as part of the [[Classic NES Series#Famicom Mini|Famicom Mini]] series, and to the [[Wii]]'s [[Virtual Console]] in the Japanese and North American regions in July 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/vc_ss/|title=VC スターソルジャー|website=www.nintendo.co.jp|access-date=2021-10-16|archive-date=2019-06-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626015941/https://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/vc_ss/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="auto">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/UDxa73mscFpG6BsKscJaLvcjq09nNcFM |title=Star Soldier for Wii - Nintendo Game Details |access-date=2021-10-16 |archive-date=2018-11-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103152900/https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/UDxa73mscFpG6BsKscJaLvcjq09nNcFM |url-status=dead}}</ref> An enhanced remake of the game was released on [[PlayStation Portable]] only in Japan in 2005.

''Star Soldier'' was re-released by [[Konami]] on the Nintendo 3DS Virtual Console on November 14, 2012, in Japan,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/titles/50010000012211|title=スターソルジャ ー &#124; ニンテンドー3DS &#124; 任天堂|website=任天堂ホームページ|access-date=2021-10-16|archive-date=2021-05-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210522000539/https://www.nintendo.co.jp/titles/50010000012211|url-status=live}}</ref> on August 15, 2013, in [[PAL]] regions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/NES/Star-Soldier-790703.html|title=Star Soldier|website=Nintendo of Europe GmbH|access-date=2021-10-16|archive-date=2021-10-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211016213157/https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/NES/Star-Soldier-790703.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and September 24 in North America, and via [[iOS]], titled {{nihongo foot|'''''Star Soldier for GREE'''''|スターソルジャー for GREE|Sutāsorujā for GREE|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} on June 20, 2013, in Japan.<ref>[http://game.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/news/20130620_604555.html ''iOS「スターソルジャーforGREE」''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055501/http://game.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/news/20130620_604555.html |date=2016-03-04}} as released and dissolved by Konami in Game Watch Impress (in Japanese)</ref>

== Legacy ==
In 2021, Konami announced a contest encouraging indie developers to make games based on some of its classic series, including ''Star Soldier''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shigeta|first=Ryuichi|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/konami-indie-games-classic-series-gradius-twinbee-goemon|title=Konami is Inviting Indie Developers to Make New Games Based on Some of Its Classic Series — Famous IP from the past may be revived through indie creators' eyes|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=October 2, 2021|access-date=2022-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211220054434/https://www.ign.com/articles/konami-indie-games-classic-series-gradius-twinbee-goemon|archive-date=2021-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref>

